<paper id="1536924747"><title>Anonymous Communication and Anonymous Cash</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="Microsoft Corp.#TAB#" id="2523988512">Daniel R. Simon</author></authors><n_citation>49</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>380217993</reference><reference>1489286008</reference><reference>1535861450</reference><reference>1542059364</reference><reference>1570307720</reference><reference>1573112122</reference><reference>1584560347</reference><reference>1594128832</reference><reference>1600709192</reference><reference>1610603564</reference><reference>1979797552</reference><reference>2004822040</reference><reference>2074594718</reference><reference>2087811006</reference><reference>2103647628</reference><reference>2115577803</reference><reference>2151413173</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-68697-5_5</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.45401">Internet privacy</keyword><keyword weight="0.41913">Existential quantification</keyword><keyword weight="0.46442">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.45164">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.57867">Electronic cash</keyword><keyword weight="0.54392">Cash</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We propose considering the problem of electronic cash in the context of a network in which anonymous, untraceable communication is assumed to be possible. We present a formal model for such a network, and define security criteria for an electronic cash system in such a setting. Finally, we show that there exists a remarkably simple electrortic cash system which meets the security criteria of the proposed model.</abstract></paper>